40|$|A timely piece proposing {{solutions}} for issues {{certain to be}} raised in the upcoming trials of <b>the</b> accused <b>Taliban</b> <b>and</b> <b>Al</b> Qaeda operatives captured in Afghanistan and detained on a U. S. military base in Cuba. In the article, I begin by examining the history and jurisdiction of Article I and Article III courts and then address the history and structure of <b>the</b> <b>Al</b> Qaeda <b>and</b> <b>Taliban</b> regimes. After considering the Constitution, federal statutes, politics, and geographical limitations, I conclude that Al Qaeda detainees should be tried in Article III courts under terrorism statutes <b>and</b> <b>Taliban</b> detainees, as military combatants, should be tried in Article I tribunals...|$|R
